---
description: Machine learning and LLM workflow standards including experiment configuration, data pipelines, prompt engineering, and model management.
globs: **/ml/**/*.py, **/models/**/*.py, **/prompts/**/*.py, **/pipelines/**/*.py, **/configs/**/*.yaml, **/experiments/**/*
alwaysApply: false
---

- **Experiment Configuration:**
  - Use `hydra` or `yaml` for clear and reproducible experiment configurations
  - Store all hyperparameters and settings in config files, never hardcode them
  - Support config overrides from command line for quick experimentation
  - Version control all configuration files

- **Data Pipeline Management:**
  - Employ scripts or tools like `dvc` to manage data preprocessing and ensure reproducibility
  - Track data versions alongside code versions
  - Document data transformations and their rationale
  - Make pipelines idempotent — re-running should produce the same output

- **Model Versioning:**
  - Utilize `git-lfs` or cloud storage (S3, GCS) to track and manage model checkpoints
  - Tag model versions with training metadata (config hash, data version, metrics)
  - Never commit large binary files directly to git

- **Experiment Logging & Tracking:**
  - Maintain comprehensive logs of experiments including parameters, results, and environmental details
  - Use `mlflow`, `tensorboard`, `wandb`, or similar for experiment tracking
  - Log metrics at regular intervals during training
  - Record the full environment (Python version, package versions, hardware) with each run

- **LLM Prompt Engineering:**
  - Dedicate a module or `prompts/` directory for managing prompt templates
  - Version control all prompt templates
  - Use template variables (Jinja2 or f-string based) for dynamic prompt construction
  - Document the purpose and expected behavior of each prompt
  - Track prompt performance metrics (accuracy, latency, cost)

- **Context Handling:**
  - Implement efficient context management for conversations
  - Use suitable data structures like `collections.deque` with `maxlen` for sliding window context
  - Implement token counting to stay within model context limits
  - Handle context overflow gracefully (summarization, truncation strategies)

- **LLM Frameworks:**
  - Use `langchain`, `transformers`, or similar frameworks as appropriate
  - Abstract LLM provider details behind a common interface for easy swapping
  - Implement retry logic with exponential backoff for API-based LLM calls

- **Demo & Prototyping:**
  - Use `gradio` or `streamlit` for building quick interactive demos
  - Keep demo code separate from production code

- **Data Processing:**
  - Use `pandas`, `numpy` for standard data processing
  - Use `dask` or `pyspark` for large-scale data processing when needed
  - Validate data at ingestion boundaries with Pydantic or custom validators

- **Hyperparameter Optimization:**
  - Use `optuna` or `hyperopt` for systematic hyperparameter search
  - Log all trial results for analysis
  - Define search spaces explicitly in configuration

- **Vector Databases:**
  - Use `faiss`, `chroma`, or similar for vector storage and similarity search
  - Index management: build, update, and persist indexes properly
  - Benchmark retrieval quality and latency
